@node Requirements "Requirements to run CINS"


    In order to use CINS you need:

 * A TCP/IP stack like AmiTCP 3.x+, Miami(Dx), TermiteTCP, AS225R2, etc.
 * Some sort of Internet connection. (PPP/SLIP, ethernet, etc.)
 * CNet/4 or better.
 * Various Internet client software (ALynx, FTP, etc.)
 * bgui.library version 41.8 or better.
@endnode

@node Features "Features of CINS"


    @{b}Features of CINS@{ub}

 * Small, fast, and resident CNetC code.  (~34k for the main executable)
 * Extensible command set (use of bbsmenu entries allows for sysop defined
   commands)
 * Easy to install.
 * Has a hotkey (beginner) and a shell based (expert) mode.  The shell mode
   uses a bbsmenu for its command set, and also allows for use of CNet's
   "Everywhere Commands".
 * Has a built in accounting system to do basic deductions on a time usage
   basis.
 * FTP/Web directory usage and accounting rates are controllable by access
   group.  Several other configuration options are settable by group as well.
 * Configuration is done via a VDE -or- GUI interface.  Configuration of
   Archie, FTP, IRC and Telnet sites is available from the GUI.
 * User directory module is very much like a CNet direct disk access
   directory.  No need for users to learn yet another cryptic program.
 * Most program text is stored in an external file (CINS:Cfg/CINS.txt), so
   as to be easily modifiable (like bbstext).
 * Executed commands are controlled by an external file, for ease of sysop
   configuration.
 * Configurable telnet/FTP/IRC server menus.
 * User configurable notebooks for FTP/Telnet/IRC/Archie.
 * Designed, developed and tested for CNet/4.
 * Maintenance module to purge out old files from user FTP directories after
   a specified number of days.
 * Web page maintenance module for users.
@endnode

@node Installation "Installing CINS"


    Installation is relatively simple.

  1)  Copy the Doors/CINS directory someplace (Doors: maybe?) and assign
      CINS: to the CINS directory.

  2)  Add the lines to bbsmenu from the "add_to_bbsmenu" file.

  3)  Add the lines to the @{b}bottom@{ub} of bbstext from the "add_to_bbstext"
      file.  Just drop them right in.  Make sure you have the line with
      "CINS Stuff" in it!  This is how CINS finds its bbstext lines!

  4)  Reload your bbstext/menu (RT in CNet/4 or RAmiga-T from Control).

  5)  Run the CINSConfig program as a CNetC program, or from a shell if
      you prefer a GUI config, and setup the configuration to your system's
      preferences.

  6)  Run CNet:Config, and in the logs section, add a new log type with the
      log ID you specified in CINSCfg with a name of CINS, or something
      similar.  This will enable CINS Logging (CNet/4 only currently).

  7)  Check path information in the CINS:Cfg/CINS.cmd file to make sure the
      path information for the executables is correct.  If you do not wish
      to use a command, just replace the line with some text to that effect.

  8)  Add it into your system in either bbsmenu, or as a CNetC executable
      menu object.
@endnode

