@node CINSEXE "The heart of CINS"


    CINS is the primary interface to the whole CINS package.  From here you
have access to Archie, FTP, Gopher, IRC, Lynx, Telnet, Talk, Finger, Ping,
Traceroute, Netstat, and the CINS utilities.  There are two modes of
operation for CINS: Menu-driven and the shell mode.

Utility     | Menu command  | Shell command
------------+---------------+-----------------------------
Archie      | A             | Archie
FTP         | F             | FTP <sitename>
Gopher      | G             | Gopher <site> <port>
IRC         | I             | IRC <site> <nick>
Lynx        | L             | Lynx <URL>
Telnet      | T             | TElnet <site> <port>
Talk        | 1             | TALk <username@site>
Finger      | V             | IFinger <username>
Ping        | P             | Ping <site>
Traceroute  | 2             | TRaceroute <site>
Netstat     | N (ID access) | Netstat (ID access required)
CINSDir     | D             | Dirmaint
CINSEdit    | C             | COnfig
CINSConfig  | ! (ID access) | <none>
CINSWeb     | W             | WEb

Assorted Notes on implementation details:

    Lack of a CINS:FTP/Menu or CINS:Telnet/Menu or a CINS:Cfg/IRC will
cause CINS to just run the program defined, without using CINS's internal
menus.  (useful for Ctelnet and CNetIRC)

    CINSConfig and Netstat require full system maintenance access in order to
run them from CINS.  This is for both security and privacy reasons.  (do you
really want your users to notice that you've been connected to www.playboy.com
for the past 3 hours?  ;)

    The shell commands are defined via the CINS bbsmenu.  Aliases may be
added, as well as additional commands.  This could be useful for things like
a Whois.rexx script or such.  The commands are checked after bbsmenu #2 so
make sure your command definitions do not conflict with that menu.  All
commands in bbsmenu #2 are available for use from within the CINS Shell.
@endnode

@node CINSConfig "The CINS Configuration Utility"


    CINSConfig allows for easier handling of the CINS.cfg file.  All
configuration is done via a VDE or a GUI interface.  When from within
CNet, you will be presented with the VDE.  From a shell you'll get the GUI.

    CINSConfig will also append a "/" to the end of the user home directory
path if one is not present, and the pathname does not end with a ":".

    CINSConfig also allows you to set, by access group, limits for FTP and
Web directory usage, as well as the rate to charge users, as well as
whether or not they have access to the upload and CD commands. (Accounting)

    Archie, FTP, IRC and Telnet menus are also fully editable from within
the GUI portion of CINSConfig.

    You can also set defaults for user preferences from within the GUI and
VDE.

   Future plans for this module:

   * ASL requester for userdir option.
@endnode

@node CINSDir "The CINS User Directory Maintenance Module"


    CINSDir handles user directory maintenance functions.  Users can
Download, tag files, delete files, read files, upload files (if allowed), and
change directories if they have them.  Pattern matching is supported for the
Dir, List, download, delete, and tag functions.  ! is also supported for
delete, for quick file deletion.  All commands in CNet's bbsmenu #2 are also
supported for usage in CINSDir.  There is also the hotkey interface for
CINSDir which is controllable from CINSEdit.
@endnode

@node CINSEdit "The CINS User Preference Editor"


    Allows the user to set their preferences for using CINS.  From here they
can set their FTP display prefs, auto-muffling when entering CINS, and
auto-shell mode when entering CINS.  If they have full ANSI support set, they
will be given a VDE to change these options.
@endnode

@node CINSMaint "The CINS Maintenance Module"


    Purges user files after the specified number of days defined in CINS.cfg
This will remove all files older than the days specified in CINS.cfg in all
user directories at this point in time, except for files beginning with a
'dot' (".")!  Also, being this is the first incarnation of this utility,
and it does delete files, be very careful in its usage.  Use it at your own
risk, as always with programs that delete files without asking.

    Future:

 * Logging of deleted files.
 * Purge user directories if there is no account by that name.
@endnode

@node CINSWeb "The CINS Web Page Maintenance Module"


   Allows users to make and modify their web pages on your system using a
similar interface to the one in CINSDir.
@endnode

@node Archie "Cfg/Archie"


    This file just contains a list of archie servers.  One server per line.
@endnode

@node CINS.acc "Cfg/CINS.acc"


    This file contains the data handled by CINSConfig/Accounting.  You should
NOT edit this file by hand!   Use the GUI!
@endnode

@node CINS.cfg "Cfg/CINS.cfg"


    This file contains the global configuration options for CINS.  This file
should only be edited using CINSConfig.
@endnode

@node CINS.cmd "Cfg/CINS.cmd"


    This file contains all the information on where programs to run for the
program functions are located, and the arguments to run them with.

    The first line is a comment (this line must exist).  The following lines
are then formatted as one line describing what the following line is used
for.  There are currently 16 commands defined in CINS.cmd.

    If you wish to disable a function in CINS (aside from Lynx and Archie), all
you need to do is replace the command line with either just an empty line or a
note to the effect of that command being disabled.

    An example CINS.cmd file:

; CINS Command Configuration file
; 0 - Telnet command line
{#2 CNet:INet/CtelNet %s}
; 1 - FTP command line
{#2 CNet:INet/CnFTP %s}
; 2 - Lynx command line (yes, there is no {#4 for this one)
ALynx %s -term ansi -show_cursor -telnet -rlogin -noprint -restrictions=file_url
; 3 - Talk command line
\\n1{#4 Talk shell %s}\\f1
; 4 - Finger command line
{#4 Finger %s}
; 5 - IRC command line
{#2 CNet:INet/CNetIRC %s %s}
; 6 - Traceroute command line
\\n1{#4 Traceroute %s}
; 7 - Netstat command line
{#4 Netstat}
; 8 - Ping (sysop) line
{#4 Ping -c5 %s}
; 9 - Ping (no maint) line
{#4 Ping %s}
; 10 - User Config util
{#2 CINS:CINSEdit}
; 11 - DirMaint util
{#2 CINS:CINSDir}
; 12 - Gopher command line
{#2 CINS:Gopher %s}
; 13 - Archie command line
Archie
; 14 - IUUMail
CNet:Doors/iuumail
; 15 - CINS Config util
{#2 CINS:CINSConfig}
; 16 - CINS Web Maint
{#2 CINS:CINSWeb
; END CINS.cmd
@endnode

@node CINS.txt "Cfg/CINS.txt"


    This file contains most of the program text, ala bbstext.  As with
bbstext, please keep lines shorter than 256 characters, and you may remove %
codes from right to left, but you must keep them in the same order.  Also do
not insert lines.  Treat it just like bbstext, as its code treats it just
about the same way as CNet treats bbstext!
@endnode

@node CINS.web "Cfg/CINS.web"


    This file contains any paths other than the default for your CNet version
to use for user web pages.  This can be useful if you do not have the
cnetaws.library module to map usernames to their CNet-supplied Web directory.
Lines in this file will have a "%s" in the line replaced with the user's MailID.
This way you could, if you wish, run user web pages out of AWS:html/<MAILID> or
InternetHome:<MAILID>/public_html.  If you specify no directories in this file
it will default to whatever is appropriate for your CNet version.

   CNet < 5.01 = Mail:Users/<MAILID>/Web
   CNet 5.01+  = Mail:Users/<MAILID>/Home/Web

   IMPORTANT!

      Do not put a trailing "/" on the directory paths!  AWS:html/%s for example
is correct but AWS:html/%s/ ISN'T!
@endnode

@node IRC "Cfg/IRC"


    This file contains a list of IRC servers to connect to in the following
format:

    Line 1: Description of server.
    Line 2: hostname of IRC server.
@endnode

@node FTPMenu "FTP/Menu"


    This file contains a short description of the kind of sites one can find
in the next layer's menu.

    Format:

    Short description of FTP/1
    Short description of FTP/2
    Short description of FTP/3
    .
    .
    .
@endnode

@node FTP# "FTP/<#>"


    This file contains a list of sites related to the topic line in the
FTP/Menu file in the following format:

    Line 1: site name
    Line 2: hostname
    Line 3: comment line #1
    Line 4: comment line #2
@endnode

@node HELP "Help/"


    This directory just contains various help files accessable via the CINS
hotkey interface's Help option.
@endnode

@node Menu "Menu/"


    This directory contains the ? help menus for CINS (shell mode) and
CINSDir (shell mode).
@endnode

@node Menus "Menus/"


    This directory contains the various displayed menu files for CINS.
Currently defined menus are:

    sys.Main:  This is the main CINS menu for the hotkey interface.
    sys.UDir:  This is displayed when a user enters the DirMaint option.
    sys.Edit:  This is displayed when a user enters the user prefs editor.

    Menus can also be prefixed with a tt#. just like the CNet SysText: files,
to define different menus for different terminal types.
@endnode

@node TelnetMenu "Telnet/Menu"


    This file contains a short description of the kind of sites one can find
in the next layer's menu.

    Format:

    Short description of Telnet/1
    Short description of Telnet/2
    Short description of Telnet/3
    .
    .
    .
@endnode

@node Telnet# "Telnet/<#>"


    This file contains a list of sites related to the topic line in the
Telnet/Menu file in the following format:

    Line 1: site name
    Line 2: hostname
    Line 3: comment line #1
    Line 4: comment line #2
@endnode

@node Text "Text/"

    This directory contains a number of files for general information and
such.  The files may be named with a leading sys. or tt[1-4]. just as most of
the SysText: files are, to allow for multiple terminal types to display
different files.

 sys.IRC      --
  This is just a short blurb explaining any IRC policies, tips, etc. you
  may have.

 sys.LongTime --
  This file is displayed when someone does a archie search with the
  output immediate.  This should be something informative to tell them
  to please wait while their search is being processed.

 sys.News     -- 
  This file will be displayed when the user logs in, if it exists.  This
  can be used for new information or just a general entry file.
@endnode

@node _CINS "User preferences file"


    This file contains the user's prefs for CINS.

    Line 1: Auto-Shell mode?    0 = No; 1 = Yes
    Line 2: Auto-Muffle?        0 = No; 1 = Yes
    Line 3: ANSI Dir/WebMaint?  0 = No; 1 = Yes
    Line 4: IRC Nick
@endnode

@node _CINSUserLimit "User Files Directory Size Limit file"


   This file is just a single line containing the maximum number of bytes
a user is allowed to have in their files directory.  It is located in their
mail directory (Mail:Users/MAILID/_CINSUserLimit)
@endnode

@node _CINSWebLimit "User Web Directory Size Limit file"


   This file is just a single line containing the maximum number of bytes
a user is allowed to have in their Web directory.  It is located in their
mail directory (Mail:Users/MAILID/_CINSWebLimit)
@endnode

@node Utilities "Some additional utilities usable with CINS"


The following Internet clients can be used with CINS and are all available
on AmiNet (in the comm/net, comm/tcp and comm/www directories). Note that
not all of these have been tested extensively, and many of them were designed
for use with AmiTCP. Some may refuse to work with other TCP stacks (Miami,
TermiteTCP, AS225, etc.)  AmiTCP and Miami users might already have some
of these applications.  If an application is marked as working, it works with
at least AmiTCP (with socket.library installed in cases of AS225 programs)
and Miami.  Links from this list lead to hints and tips to using the program.

Type        | Filename                          | Notes
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Archie     | comm/net/archie141.lha            | Not tested
            | comm/tcp/archie38.1.lha           | Works
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Finger     | comm/tcp/amitcp_finger.lha        | Not tested
            | comm/tcp/Finger.lha               | Not tested
            | comm/net/FingerInfo10.lha         | Not tested
            | AmiTCP finger                     | Works
            | MiamiFinger                       | Works
            | CNet/4 Internal Finger            | Works
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 FTP        | comm/tcp/AmiTCP_ncftp156.lha      | Newer version in AmiTCP
            |                                   |  (works)
            | @{" CNet/4 CnFTP " link CnFTP}                   | Works (See note)
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Gopher     | comm/tcp/BBGopher10.lha           | CNetC/4 alternative in CINS
            |                                   |  4.x archive.
            | comm/tcp/gopher.lha               | Not tested
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 IRC        | comm/tcp/AmIRCii-2.8.2.lha        | Unix IRC port
            | comm/tcp/irchat24.lha             | Not tested
            | CNet/4 CNetIRC                    | Works
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
@{" Lynx " link ALynx}      | comm/www/ALynx.lha                | Works
            | comm/www/ALynx_AS225exe.lha       | Works (AS225/socket.library)
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 POP3 Client| rPOP3/CrPOP3                      | CNetC/4 as CINS Utility
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Talk       | comm/tcp/AmiTALK155.lha           | Works
            | comm/net/Talk.lha                 | Not tested
            | comm/tcp/ytalk1_0a.lha            | Not tested
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Telnet     | comm/tcp/amitcp_telnet.lha        | Works
            | comm/net/telnet.lha               | Works (AS225/socket.library)
            | Default AmiTCP telnet             | Works
            | @{" CNet/4 CtelNet " link Ctelnet}                 | Works (see note)
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
 Traceroute | comm/tcp/AtcpTraceroute.lha       | Not tested
            | comm/tcp/Traceroute1_17.lha       | Not tested
            | AmiTCP Traceroute                 | Works
            | MiamiTraceroute                   | Works
            | CNet/4 Traceroute                 | Works
------------+-----------------------------------+---------------------------
@endnode

@node ALynx "ALynx Tips and Tricks"


    Hints and tricks for using ALynx with CINS.

Q:  ALynx looks very Christmasy. (Red and green ANSI).  How can I change
    this?
A:  Issue a "SetEnv CURSESANSICOLORS 77234567" in a shell, followed by "Copy
    ENV:CURSESANSICOLORS ENVARC:" to make the change permanent.  This will
    make the red turn to white.
@endnode

@node CnFTP "CNet FTP Notes"


   Currently CNetFTP when run from an MCI command, such as in CINS, requires
the O=21 argument to it when a host is also specified in the MCI command.
(last checked with 4.55)

@endnode

@node Ctelnet "CNet Telnet Notes"


   Ctelnet does has a command line option to enable localecho mode
(required by most all MUDs and some services to see what you're typing).
To enable this option you need to use the format:

site.com <port #> DOECHO

   Also note: some MUDs seem to have problems with the initial negotiation
and will fill in the first prompt presented upon connect with garbage input.

@endnode

